{"parse":{"title":"heap","pageid":61966,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Heap|Hieb}}\n==English==\n{{wp}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|hepe}}, from {{inh|en|ang|hēap}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*haup}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*haupaz}} (compare {{cog|nl|hoop}}, {{cog|nds-de|Hupen}}, {{cog|de|Haufen}}), from {{der|en|ine-pro|*koupos||hill}} (compare {{cog|lt|kaũpas}}, {{cog|sq|qipi||stack}}, {{cog|ae|𐬐𐬂𐬟𐬀}}).\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{enPR|hēp}}, {{IPA|en|/hiːp/}}\n* {{a|en|Ireland|dated}} {{enPR|hāp}}, {{IPA|en|/heːp/}}\n* {{audio|en|en-us-heap.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{rhymes|en|iːp|s=1}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# A [[crowd]]; a [[throng]]; a multitude or great number of people.\n#* {{RQ:Bacon Holy War|104|A '''Heap''' of Vassals, and Slaues: {{...}} A People that is without ''Naturall Affection'', {{...}} A ''Nation'' without Morality, without Letters, Arts, or Sciences}}\n#* {{RQ:Trollope Doctor Thorne|passage=He had plenty of friends, '''heaps''' of friends in the parliamentary sense}}\n# A [[pile]] or [[mass]]; a collection of things laid in a body, or thrown together so as to form an elevation.\n#: {{ux|en|a '''heap''' of earth; a '''heap''' of stones}}\n#* {{RQ:Dryden Aeneis|passage=Huge '''heaps''' of slain around the body rise.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=May 9, 2012| author=Jonathan Wilson| title=Europa League: Radamel Falcao's Atlético Madrid rout Athletic Bilbao| work=the Guardian| url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2012/may/09/atletico-madrid-athletic-bilbao-europa-league| passage=Every break seemed dangerous and Falcao clearly had the beating of Amorebieta. Others, being forced to stretch a foot behind them to control Arda Turan's 34th-minute cross, might simply have lashed a shot on the turn; Falcao, though, twisted back on to his left foot, leaving Amorebieta in a '''heap''', and thumped in an inevitable finish – his 12th goal in 15 European matches this season.}}\n# A great number or large quantity of things.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1679|author=w:Gilbert Burnet|title=The History of the Reformation of the Church of England\n|passage=a vast '''heap''', both of places of scripture and quotations}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1878|author=w:Robert Louis Stevenson|title=s:Will o' the Mill\n|passage=I have noticed a '''heap''' of things in my life.}}\n# {{lb|en|computing}} A [[data structure]] consisting of [[tree]]s in which each [[node]] is greater than all its [[child]]ren.\n# {{lb|en|computing}} Memory that is dynamically allocated.\n#: {{ux|en|You should move these structures from the stack to the '''heap''' to avoid a potential stack overflow.}}\n# {{lb|en|colloquial}} A [[dilapidated]] [[place]] or [[vehicle]].\n#: {{ux|en|My first car was an old '''heap'''.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|date=May 12 1991|chapter=[[w:List of Jeeves and Wooster episodes|Kidnapped!]]|title=w:Jeeves and Wooster|section=Series 2, Episode 5\n|passage=''Chuffy:'' It's on a knife edge at the moment, Bertie. If he can get planning permission, old Stoker's going to take this '''heap''' off my hands in return for vast amounts of [[oof]].}}\n# {{lb|en|colloquial}} A [[lot]], a large amount.\n#: {{ux|en|Thanks a '''heap'''!}}\n#* {{RQ:Thackeray Pendennis||passage=[W]e went to the play, and Pen was struck all of a '''heap''' with Miss Fotheringay … And he’s fallen in love with her—and I’m blessed if he hasn’t proposed to her {{…}}|10}}\n\n====Synonyms====\n* See also [[Thesaurus:lot]]\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en|aheap|all of a heap|ant-heap|antheap|ash-heap|ash-heap-cake|ash heap of history|at the top of the heap|compost heap|dung-heap|dung heap|dustheap|dust heap of history|garbage heap of history|Heap Bridge|heaper|heapful|heapmeal|heapsort|heapy|it takes a heap of living to make a house a home|it takes a heap o' livin' to make a house a home|junkheap|minheap|moleheap|muckheap|mudheap|sandheap|scrap-heap|scrap heap|scrapheap|semiheap|shellheap|shitheap|slag heap|spoil heap|subheap|thanks a heap|to-heap|trash heap of history|treap}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|srn|ipi}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|crowd}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|тълпа|f}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|mensenmassa|m|f}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|joukko}}, {{t+|fi|väkijoukko}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|multitude|f}}, {{t|gl|moitedume|f}}, {{t+|gl|chea|f}}, {{t|gl|corxa|f}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Menschenmenge|f}}, {{t+|de|Masse|f}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|folla|f}}, {{t+|it|massa|f}}, {{t+|it|moltitudine|f}}\n* Occitan: {{t+|oc|molon|m}}, {{t+|oc|molonada|f}}, {{t+|oc|multitud|f}}, {{t+|oc|fola|f}}, {{t+|oc|mond|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|multidão|f}}\n* Quechua: {{t|qu|qisa}}\n* Uyghur: {{t|ug|غۇژمەك}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top-see|pile}}\n* Arabic:\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{t|arz|كومة|f|tr=kōma}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|կույտ}}, {{t+|hy|զանգված}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t|az|qalaq}}, {{t|az|yığın}}, {{t|az|topa}}\n* Basque: {{t|eu|pilo}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|ку́ча|f}}, {{t|be|ку́па|f}}\n* Bhojpuri: {{t|bho|ढेर}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|куп|m}}, {{t+|bg|купчина|f}}\n* Chechen: {{t|ce|гӏама}}\n* Cherokee: {{t|chr|ᎤᎪᏗᏗ}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|堆|tr=duī}}\n* Danish: {{t|da|stak|c}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|hoop|m}}, {{t+|nl|berg|m}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|stako}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kasa}}, {{t+|fi|läjä}}, {{t+|fi|keko}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|tas|m}}, {{t+|fr|pile|f}}, {{t+|fr|monceau|m}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|pía|f}}, {{t|gl|conxerie|f}}, {{t+|gl|morea|f}}, {{t|gl|rebullón|m}}, {{t|gl|moutillón|m}}, {{t|gl|cómaro|m}}, {{t|gl|toutelo|m}}, {{t+|gl|cemba|f}}, {{t|gl|cotarelo|m}}, {{t|gl|alarve|m}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|გროვა}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Haufen|m}}, {{t+|de|Haufe|m}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|σωρός|m}}, {{t+|el|στοίβα|f}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|σωρός|m}}, {{t|grc|σώρευμα|n}}, {{t|grc|θίς|m}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|ढेर|m}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|halom}}\n* Ingrian: {{t|izh|mytty}}, {{t|izh|koko}}, {{t|izh|ropja}}, {{t|izh|runni}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|dumha|m}}, {{t|ga|carnán|m}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|pila}}, {{t+|it|cumulo}}, {{t+|it|catasta|f}}, {{t+|it|mucchio|m}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|重ね|tr=かさね, kasane}}, {{t+|ja|塚|tr=つか, tsuka}}, {{t+|ja|堆積|tr=たいせき, taiseki}}, {{t+|ja|積み重ね|tr=つみかさね, tsumikasane}}, {{t+|ja|山|tr=[[やま]], yama}}\n* Khmer: {{t+|km|គំនរ|tr=kumnɔɔ}}, {{t+|km|ពំនូក|tr=pumnuuk}}, {{t+|km|រនះ|tr=rɔneah}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|더미}}, {{t+|ko|무더기}}\n* Latgalian: {{t|ltg|guba}}, {{t|ltg|gobona}}, {{t|ltg|kryva}}, {{t|ltg|skaudze}}, {{t|ltg|grāda}}\n* Latin: {{t|la|struēs|f}}, {{t+|la|acervus|m}}, {{t|la|cumulus|m}}\n* Latvian: {{t|lv|kaudze}}, {{t|lv|grēda}}, {{t|lv|čupa}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t|lt|krūvà|f}}, {{t|lt|kaũpas|m}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|куп|m}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|purawhetū}}, {{t|mi|taupū}}, {{t|mi|kōputu}}\n* Mari:\n*: Eastern Mari: {{t|mhr|курык}}\n* Mongolian: {{t-needed|mn}}\n* Occitan: {{t+|oc|molon|m}}, {{t|oc|pièla|f}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|کپه|tr=koppe}}, {{t+|fa|توده|tr=tude}}, {{t+|fa|کوت|tr=kut}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|sterta|f}}, {{t+|pl|kupa|f}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|pilha|f}}, {{t+|pt|monte|m}}\n* Quechua: {{t|qu|qutu}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|groapă|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|ку́ча|f}}, {{t+|ru|гру́да|f}}, {{t+|ru|во́рох|m}}, {{t+|ru|ки́па|f}}\n* Sanskrit: {{t+|sa|निचय|m}}, {{t+|sa|राशि|m|f}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|pila|f}}, {{t+|es|montón|m}}, {{t+|es|cúmulo|m}}\n* Thai: {{t-needed|th}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|öbek}}\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{t|ota|ییغین|tr=yığın}}, {{t|ota|كومه|tr=küme}}\n* Ugaritic: {{t|uga|𐎖𐎎𐎕}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|ку́па|f}}, {{t|uk|ку́ча|f}}\n* Uyghur: {{t|ug|غارام}}, {{t|ug|دۈۋە}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|đống}}, {{t+|vi|gò}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|moncea|m}}, {{t+|wa|hopea|m}}\n* Welsh: {{t+|cy|pentwr}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|great number or large quantity of things}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|маса|f}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|berg|m}}, {{t+|nl|massa|f}}, {{t+|nl|massa|m|f}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|joukko}}, {{t+|fi|kasa}}, {{t+|fi|läjä}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|tas|m}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|pía|f}}, {{t|gl|parga|f}}, {{t|gl|conxerie|f}}, {{t+|gl|acervo|m}}, {{t+|gl|morea|f}}, {{t|gl|rebullón|m}}, {{t+|gl|monte|m}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|moltitudine|f}}, {{t+|it|massa|f}}, {{t+|it|marea|f}}\n* Occitan: {{t+|oc|molon|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|monte|m}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|ку́ча|f|tr=}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|type of data structure}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|pila|f}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|堆|tr=duī}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|halda|f}}\n* Dutch: {{t-needed|nl}}\n* Esperanto: {{t-needed|eo}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|keko}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|tas|m}}, {{t+|fr|pile}}\n* German: {{t|de|Heap|m}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|σωρός|f}}\n* Japanese: {{t|ja|ヒープ|tr=hīpu}}\n* Norwegian: {{t|no|heap}}\n* Occitan: {{t+|oc|molon|m}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|kopiec|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{t|pt|heap|m|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|ку́ча|f}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|montículo|m}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|heap|c}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|öbek}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|memory that is dynamically allocated}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|keko}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|ку́ча|f|tr=}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|colloquial: dilapidated place or vehicle}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|таратайка|f}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|rämä}}, {{t+|fi|romu}}, {{t|fi|romukasa}} {{q|vehicle, device}}; {{t+|fi|roska}}\n* Portuguese: {{t|pt|carripana|f}}, {{t+|pt|calhambeque|m}}, {{t+|pt|chaço|m}}, {{t|pt|chaço-velho|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|colloquial: large amount}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|vuori}}; {{t|fi|jätti-}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{checktrans-top}}\n* Albanian: {{t+check|sq|grumbull|m}}\n* Basque: {{t+check|eu|meta}}\n* Catalan: {{t+check|ca|munt|m}}, {{t+check|ca|pila|f}}\n* Czech: {{t+check|cs|hromada|f}}, {{t+check|cs|kupa|f}}\n* Dutch: {{t+check|nl|hoop|m}}\n* Esperanto: {{t-check|eo|monteto}}\n* French: {{t+check|fr|tas|m}}\n* Frisian:\n*: West Frisian: {{t-check|fy|heap}}\n* Italian: {{qualifier|1|2}} {{t+check|it|mucchio|m}}, {{qualifier|3}} {{t+check|it|cumulo|m}}\n* Malay: {{t-check|ms|melambak}}\n* Serbo-Croatian: {{t+check|sh|hrpa|f}}, {{t+check|sh|gomila|f}}\n* Slovak: {{t-check|sk|kopa|f}}\n* Slovene: {{t+check|sl|kup|m}}\n* Swedish: {{t+check|sv|hop|c}}\n* Telugu: {{t+check|te|కుప్ప}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To pile in a heap.\n#: {{ux|en|He '''heaped''' the laundry upon the bed and began folding.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To form or round into a heap, as in measuring.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1819|author=[[:w:John Keats|John Keats]]|title=Otho the Great|section=act I, scene II|line_plain=verses 40-42\n|passage=Cry a reward, to him who shall first bring <br> News of that vanished Arabian, <br> A full-'''heap’d''' helmet of the purest gold.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To supply in great quantity.\n#: {{ux|en|They '''heaped''' praise upon their newest hero.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2022 January 12|author=Nigel Harris|title=Comment: Unhappy start to 2022|journal=RAIL|issue=948|page=3|text=Then, in January, a creeping tsunami of train cancellations, triggered by major staff absences as a result of the aggressive transmissibility of Omicron, '''heaped''' further misery on rail users.}}\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{sense|pile in a heap}} {{l|en|amass}}, {{l|en|heap up}}, {{l|en|pile up}}; see also [[Thesaurus:pile up]]\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en|heapability|heapable|upheap|heap coals of fire on someone's head|{{l|en|heaped|pos=adj}}, {{l|en|heaping|pos=adj}}|heap on|heap up|overheap|heap insult on injury}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|to pile in a heap}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|натрупвам}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kasata}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|στοιβάζω}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|χόω}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|ammucchiare}}, {{t+|it|ammassare}}, {{t+|it|accatastare}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|whakataipū}}, {{t|mi|whakapīhangaiti}}, {{t|mi|haipū}}, {{t|mi|tarahono}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|empilhar}}, {{t+|pt|amontoar}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|amontonar}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to form or round into a heap}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kasata}}, {{t+|fi|läjittää}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|στοιβάζω}}\n* Italian: {{t|it|ricolmare}}, {{t+|it|ricoprire}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|amontoar}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|amontonar}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to supply in great quantity}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|отрупвам}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|הִרְעִיף|tr=hir'íf}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|colmare}}, {{t|it|ricolmare}}, {{t+|it|coprire}}, {{t+|it|sommergere}}, {{t+|it|riempire}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|amontonar}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{checktrans-top}}\n* Dutch: {{t+check|nl|hopen}}\n* German: {{t+check|de|Haufen}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{en-adv|-}}\n\n# {{lb|en|possibly|offensive}} [[very]] or [[much]]; {{ng|representing broken English stereotypically or comically attributed to [[Native American]]s}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1895|author=Annie Maria Barnes|title=Matouchon: A Story of Indian Child Life|page=175\n|passage=Chuckaway too no good. '''Heap''' water, little chuckaway. '''Heap''' sticks, and still little chuckaway.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1980|author=Joey Lee Dillard|title=Perspectives on American English|page=417\n|passage=We are all familiar with the stereotyped broken English which writers of Western stories, comic strips, and similar literature put into the mouths of Indians: 'me '''heap''' big chief', 'you like um fire water', and so forth.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2004|author=John Robert Colombo|title=The Penguin Book of Canadian Jokes|page=175\n|passage=Once upon a time, a Scotsman, an Englishman, and an Irishman are captured by the Red Indians {{...}} He approaches the Englishman, pinches the skin of his upper arm, and says, \"Hmmm, '''heap''' good skin, nice and thick.}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=aehp|HAPE|HEPA|epha|hep A}}\n\n{{cln|en|positive polarity items}}\n\n==Old English==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{dercat|ang|gem-pro|inh=1}}\nFrom {{inh|ang|gmw-pro|*haup}}.\n\nCognate with {{cog|ofs|hāp}}, {{cog|osx|hōp}}, {{cog|goh|houf}}. {{cog|non|hópr}} differs from the expected form ''*haupr'' because it is a borrowing from {{w|Middle Low German}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ang-IPA|hēap}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{ang-noun|m|head=hēap}}\n\n# [[group]]\n#* '''c. 992''', [[w:Ælfric of Eynsham|Ælfric]], \"[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Homilies_of_the_Anglo-Saxon_Church/XXVII The Nativity of St. Paul the Apostle]\"\n#*: {{quote|ang|[Petrus] āna spræc for ealne þone '''hēap'''.|[Peter] by himself spoke for the whole '''group'''.}}\n#* [https://archive.org/details/anglosaxonchroni01thor/page/224/mode/1up The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]\n#*: {{quote|ang|''Đǣr wæs prēosta '''hēap''',<br/>miċel muneca ðrēat,<br/>mīne ġefrēġe<br/>glēawra ġegaderod.''|There was a '''group''' of priests,<br/>a throng of many monks,<br/> of wise ones gathered,<br/>so I've heard<br/>}}\n# [[#English|heap]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{ang-decl-noun-a-m|hēap}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|ang|hēapmǣlum}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desctree|enm|hepe}}\n\n==Portuguese==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{ubor|pt|en|heap}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{pt-noun|mf|#s}}\n\n# {{lb|pt|computing}} {{l|en|heap}} {{gloss|tree-based data structure}}\n\n==West Frisian==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|fy|ofs|hāp}}, from {{inh|fy|gmw-pro|*haup}}, from {{inh|fy|gem-pro|*haupaz|t=heap}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{fy-noun|c|heapen|pl2=heappen|heapke}}\n\n# [[#English|heap]], [[pile]]\n# [[mass]], [[gang]], [[horde]]\n\n====Further reading====\n* {{R:WFT|37879}}"}}